The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | Alert prompts CM review
                                                                                                                         3                                                                                      Alert prompts CM review
          A STAFF REPORTER                              
	Chief minister Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee on Tuesday met senior officials, including the police brass, and discussed security arrangements in Calcutta and its adjoining areas a day after the Centre alerted the state about a terror threat.         
	The meeting was attended by chief secretary Ashok Mohan Chakrabarti, the director-general of police, Bhupinder Singh, and police commissioner Gautam Mohan Chakrabarti.        
	On Monday, home secretary Ardhendu Sen had revealed that the Union home ministry had sent a message to the state that Taliban and Lashkar-e-Toiba operatives might trigger blasts in select cities, including Calcutta, Delhi and Mumbai.        
	We have strengthened the security in Calcutta. Police and intelligence officers of the states mentioned in the message are working together, the police commissioner said after the meeting.         
	Sen later said: Till now there is no information that terrorists have entered Calcutta.... However, we have beefed up security across the city.         
	Singh stressed the need to step up vigil along the coast and met officials of Garden Reach Ship Builders about supplying 28 intercepting speedboats. The state has already received two such boats.         
	N.P.S. Aulakh, the director-general of National Security Guards, met senior officials and top cops on Tuesday and pointed out that the police should have plans of the citys key installations.                                                                                                                                                          
